This includes the following changes
- Model Rotation
  - Validators can now host any number of models. These are rotated out each
    interval randomly. Valis are guaranteed to send at least 1 verifiable request

  - Validators now self-monitor for system hangs. If no requests are
    successfully sent within 5 minutes, validators will auto-restart. This is
    opt-in, and can be enabled with an env file. See readme for details, under
    the `Validator .env` header.
- Bittensor 8.4.5
  - Bumped bittensor version to help with stability when connecting to the chain

  - Jugo now has more sane timeouts (1 min)

No updates needed, however you are free to pull down new source code and update to newer bittensor version.

1) Delete the .venv file in your targon directory
2) Create new .venv
3) pull down new source code
4) pip install -e .
5) restart via pm2

To enable heartbeat, add a `.env` file in the targon directory, containing the following lines

HEARBEAT=True

the vali architecture is a bit complicated

so we support a completely arbitrary amount of models. each vali determins what models they want to run. most valis use targon hubs endpoint to get the list of models targon hub requests (which is what our validator will always request, so valis will generally use this to stay in consensus). smaller valis want to keep costs low so they only validate using a single a100. this means they can only validate models that fit on an a100 (hence why a lot of small valis only request a few models). the larger valis generally run on 8 boxes, and can support models up to 8 gpu worth. that's where the vali model limits come from. 

each vali, ever interval, will grab the requested models from whatever source they decide (again, most use targon huh). this list is randomly sorted, and valis will start as many models as they can until they run out of GPUs. from there, they will query synthetics for *every* model they *could possibly* run, and every few requests is guaranteed to be one that the vali *is* validating. validators will only post validated requests to targon hub.

I turned off my auto-reg scripts to reduce my footprint over time and eventually get eliminated.  But I will provide some of my keys to success here:
• 8x h100 sxm nodes in Dallas Texas area for most of the smaller models, meaning minimum one 8x node per model but actually more than that if you run several uids
• 8x h200 boxes for the 30b+ models and especially deepseek
• use num-scheduler-steps 8-24 depending on model size with the multi-step-stream-outputs option
• enable prefix cache for the models used for organics, especially the envy/dippy model, most organic usage is prompts that build on each other
• use nginx with a map directive to handle the targon model header to route to the appropriate underlying vllm upstream
• pay attention to response data and what the validator needs from each response
• disable scheduler steps for deepseek, disable chunked prefill, concurrency limit of like 4-5 to avoid crashes, verify the sampling params because they have bugs in the engine
• find a strategy to handle subsequent duplicate or near duplicate requests so the engine can be more efficient, e.g. route to specific nodes by prompt prefix
• disable logging, stats collection, and telemetry
• make the models endpoint database driven with a background process to automatically provision new nodes (I used the shadeform API with filters on location and GPU types) when a new model is detected. I used ansible to automate driver/vllm/etc. install and it auto-updated the neuron upon completion. Just be sure to account for model config, kv heads and attention heads need to be divisible by tensor parallelism, so for example phi-4 could only run 2x TP, qwen coder small was tp4, the rest tp8

It used to be the case that multi-region setup was critical, and at that time I had anycast routing via GCP global load balancers to Dallas, Paris, and Syndey, but now the manifold vali has so much stake that it's not really necessary.
